The term "teacher effect" is used to describe the influence that educators have on their students. Effective instructors may have a beneficial effect on student outcomes including test scores, graduation rates, and college enrollment, as has been proved by extensive research. Teachers are crucial to the success of any educational system, but they are not the sole determinant. Classrooms, textbooks, and technology are all examples of infrastructural resources that must be thought about, as well as the educational system as a whole and the rules that govern it. To ensure that all people have access to an education of "inclusive and equitable quality" (SDG 4), we must eliminate barriers to learning such as poverty, prejudice, and a lack of financial resources. Access to early childhood education, teaching in different languages, and accommodating students with special needs are all strategies that may bolster inclusive education. To guarantee that all kids have access to the resources and assistance they need to thrive in school, policies and programs that address poverty, such as school food programs and cash transfers, can be implemented. Therefore, enhancing the quality of education requires a number of interrelated measures, just one of which is an increase in the supply of trained instructors. If we are to realize the vision of excellent education that is accessible to all, regardless of background or financial situation, this initiative must be paired with others that aim to strengthen the educational system as a whole and combat structural disparities. 